40|$|This article {{discusses}} a {{trend of}} <b>Direct</b> <b>Costing</b> in 19702 ̆ 7 s in the U. S. In the early 19702 ̆ 7 s, {{there were some}} insistence on an application of <b>Direct</b> <b>Costing</b> for tax reporting purpose. And the controversy of <b>Direct</b> <b>Costing,</b> Fekrat versus Gordon=Cook and Largy, was occurred. In 1973,the Federal Income Tax Regulation was revised. In the early 19702 ̆ 7 s the CASB was settled. They supported the full absorption basis for inventory costing. They {{put an end to}} the controversy of application of <b>Direct</b> <b>Costing</b> for external reporting. In the same time, some researchers applied mathematical programming to Cost Accounting. They pointed out some defects of <b>Direct</b> <b>Costing</b> and advantages of Full Costing, which were said as advantages of <b>Direct</b> <b>Costing...</b>|$|R
40|$|Includes bibliographical {{references}} (pages 69 - 70) The {{objective of}} this research has been to examine the nature and usefulness of <b>direct</b> <b>costing.</b> After a chapter that presented the historical background {{and the development of}} the <b>direct</b> <b>cost</b> concept and which was included in the research to lend perspective and understanding, the study considered cost classifications and analyzed the usefulness of <b>direct</b> <b>costing</b> for management decision purposes and for external financial reporting. The study also presented a profit sensitivity model so that attention could be focused on the variance in results obtained under <b>direct</b> <b>costing</b> as compared to the results obtained using absorption costing. This model was included in the study for completeness {{on the assumption that the}} evaluation of <b>direct</b> <b>costing</b> should not be limited to a consideration of its differences in theory and application, but also its impact on profits as compared to other costing methods. The central conclusions of this study are listed below. 1. The nature of <b>direct</b> <b>costing</b> is found in the association of fixed or time costs of production with time periods rather than with units of product. 2. <b>Direct</b> <b>cost</b> statements help make management aware of patterns of cost behavior and relevant cost classifications and thus aid in solving decision problems. 3. <b>Direct</b> <b>costing</b> presents income statements where the fluctuation in income is related to the fluctuations in sales, rather than to the fluctuation in both sales and production, and can aid in evaluating efficiency. 4. <b>Direct</b> <b>costing</b> has not had general acceptance for published financial reports even though it may be used for planning and controlling purposes. Because the criteria applied in the case of <b>direct</b> <b>costing</b> differ from the criteria applied for absorption costing, the controversy over the use of <b>direct</b> or absorption <b>costing</b> for external reports will persist. 5. The impact of <b>direct</b> <b>costing</b> for profit determination as demonstrated by the sensitivity model developed for the study is significant even for reasonably low proportions of fixed overhead cost and relatively balanced production and sales volumes...|$|R
40|$|AbstractAccident cost {{estimation}} {{become more important}} since it may cause financial implication to the company. However, there are no consensus between researchers in classifying <b>direct</b> <b>cost</b> component. The objective {{of this study is}} to evaluate <b>direct</b> <b>cost</b> model of occupational accident cost by using confirmatory factor analysis (CFA) method. There are three cost components proposed for <b>direct</b> <b>cost</b> estimation which are medical cost, rehabilitation cost and compensation cost. Local specific approach (by reviewing previous accident record in the company) is adopted in data collection process and only accidents occurred between 2008 and 2013 were considered in this study. There are 344 cases in total which came from six different sectors in manufacturing industry. For each occupational accident, the site safety officer in charge, human resource and account department officer were interviewed in order to estimate the <b>direct</b> <b>cost.</b> Then, the relationship between three observed variables for <b>direct</b> <b>cost</b> is evaluated by using CFA. The CFA result shows that the occupational accident <b>direct</b> <b>cost</b> model has acceptable goodness of fit that proved relationship between three observed variables (medical, rehabilitation and compensation cost) and its latent construct. In conclusion, the model justify that <b>direct</b> <b>cost</b> consists of three components, which are medical cost, rehabilitation cost and compensation cost...|$|R
