25|$|The {{impact of}} cyanobacterial blooms has been {{assessed}} in economic terms. In December 1991, the world’s largest algal bloom occurred in Australia, where 1000nbsp&km of the Darling-Barwon River was affected. One million people-days {{of drinking water}} were lost, and the <b>direct</b> <b>costs</b> incurred totalled more than A$1.3 million. Moreover, 2000 site-days of recreation were also lost, and the economic cost was estimated at A$10 milliobn, after taking into account indirectly affected industries such as tourism, accommodation and transport.|$|E
